<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-377-212  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 377 212.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 16 1990 v9 n8 p71(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>If you consider volume of buys, protest is rare. (Fedwatch)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Accounting OfficeLaw SuitData ProcessingGovernment AgencyComputer IndustryCompetitive BiddingReports.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>If You Consider Volume of Buys, Protest Is RareandM;The General Accounting Office recently conducted an exhaustive study of ADPprotests to determine if there is a real problem with agencies buying offprotesters with large settlements.andM;GAO concluded there are few protests, given the total number of procurementactions.andP;  It also found most protest decisions are made in well under the 45working days required by law.andM;As for payments made under settlements, the congressional watchdog foundthat, except for a Census Bureau settlement of $1.1 million, most paymentswere under $35,000.andM;In three cases, some of the money for the settlement came from the winningbidder -- not the agency.andP;  This lays to rest the fear that &quot;Fedmail&quot; is asignificant problem.andM;I have said before that there are very few protests for the number of ADPprocurement actions.andP;  Occasionally agencies do screw up a procurement.andP;  Theyshould be allowed to make a business decision to reach a settlement --including a payoff.andP;  GAO correctly recommends that the details of thesesettlements be made public so there is no question of improper activity.andP;  GAOalso said any payments should come from the agency's appropriation.andM;It is time our industry acknowledges that, with rare exceptions, governmentADP procurement staffs fo a terrific job.andP;  When you consider the god-awfulnumber of rules they must follow, it is a wonder anything ever gets bought.andM;The shortage of trained people and the absolute perfection demanded by theprotest tribunals significantly narrows the odds of a successful buy.andO;Private industry never would tolerate such nonsense.andM;Perhaps future protest decisions should include a financial impact statementthat quantifies the potential effect of sustaining a protest and delaying aprocurement.andM;Protests based on some minor violations have delayed the Air Force'sStrategic War Planning System, the Desktop Companion and Desktop IIIprocurements.andP;  These delays cost millions of dollars.andP;  A more reasonabledecision process, including payoffs, might be warranted.andM;Bob Dornan is vice president of Federal Sources Inc., Vienna, Va.andO;</TEXT></DOC>